title: For Sale:  Old store ammo prices
postcontent: Is it just me or does it seem ridiculous that some sellers on here want to trade thier guns that are marked at current prices, for ammo only if it is adjusted to reflect old store prices?  Trust me, I'm no price gouging ammo hoarder, but if I want to buy factory ammo now, I'm going to pay the price or wait.  Just like gas - no one who  bought gas at a dollar a gallon is going to sell it for that price when it is four bucks a gallon.  Obviously, everyone has thier price, but if you want old store prices on ammo, then you better be willing to take old store prices on the gun you are trying to trade.  Seems like too many people are trying to turn a fair deal into one that will profit themselves.  Sure, that's business, but its disappointing when our "community" has sunk to the level of the corporate profitability mentality, instead of treating each other as equal members (brethren) of the shooting community.

title: For Sale:  Crossman Benjamin .22 air rifle
postcontent:
First things first: This is not your kid's Red Rider BB gun! I've taken down rabbits, squirrels, and even raccoons with this air gun. It has some serious takedown power for small game. It is very accurate and can take down a rabbit at 100+ yards with good shot placement. 

Secondly, it is extremely quiet. If you're looking to do some squirrel control in the city, or maybe just do some backyard plinking, this is your gun. Your neighbors won't even hear it! Depending on what you're shooting at, many times its louder when the bullet impacts the target than when it leaves the barrel. 

The gun is a break action - like a breech-loaded shotgun, kinda. Opening the breech also pumps the gun; no need to pump after you load it.

Mounted on the gun is a fixed magnification Center Point scope that I've been more than happy with. A better scope might be nice if you're going to do some serious hunting, but I've been nothing but happy with this one so far. 

It shoots .22 caliber pellets, not the typical .177 "BB caliber." These have more takedown power than .177. Although hollow point "hunting pellets" are available, I prefer round nose pellets. These seem to maintain good penetration past 50 yards, without over penetrating at closer distances. I will include some of each with the sale. 

I bought the gun for small game hunting and used it extensively until I bought my 10/22. I'm selling to buy some parts to trick out my 10/22. 

This would make a great first gun for a kid, but kids of any age (including middle-age!) will have fun with this.

title: For Sale:  # 334274601
postcontent: This is a Smith & Wesson .357 Registered Magnum that was a special build in 1936, with registration number 845. This number is stamped on the yoke cut (REG.845). The serial number is stamped on the inside of the barrel shroud and on the butt of the frame. There is a small SW logo on the left side plate. With the serial number, registration number and the small logo, this is one of the early production models, mfg 1936. It has a 6” pinned barrel, a King front sight and adjustable rear sight. It is a six shot with a counter-bored cylinder. It is a 5 screw, square butt target frame, and the finish is bright blue. Does show some holster wear on the end of the barrel and some handling wear, but overall the original finish is very good. The grips are original diamond checkered walnut type grips for the .357 Registered Magnum. They are not original to the firearm, but are correct for this model. Locks up tight and has a good bore. This model has a spring-loaded ball bearing in the yoke to assist locking the cylinder open. The topstrap and barrel rib are finely checkered. The top of the hammer is also finely checkered. postcontent:

- Original Box.

- Meprolight Night Sights.
- Backstraps.
- Speed Loader.
- Gun Lock.
- Papers.

Ejector Code: 30274.

Gun was purchased in FEB 2013.
Night sights were purchased and installed a couple weeks ago.
Only 50 rounds fired. Functions perfect! No erratic ejections or brass to face.
Gun is still in immaculate condition and you can't even tell its been fired.

Want to trade only for:

Glock 17 Gen 4. Must come with original box and 3 - 17 round Glock magazines (no Korean KCI mags), the backstraps and extended rear pin, and of course the original contents (papers, speed loader, gun lock, cleaning brush).
Must be of recent production, between OCT 2012 - present. Models that were produced before OCT 2012 had the 336 ejector. The 336 ejectors were causing erratic ejection issues like brass to the face, FTF, FTE, stovepipe, etc. Glock noticed the problem and started putting in 30274 ejectors into their Glock 17 and 19 gen 4 pistols, as well as gen 3 pistols.

I have 3 extra 15 round Glock mags that I will be willing to trade for 3 - 17 round Glock mags. That means I have 6 total 15 round mags that I would like to trade for 6 - 17 round mags. I will throw in the new night sights for free. I will not charge anything extra or need anything extra for the night sights.
